sec.p:
These methods of production share two important characteristics. First, the peak period’s long‐run marginal cost (MC) exceeds the off‐peak period’s marginal cost no matter which policy the supplier uses because changes in peak demand affect capacity or inventory costs. This difference between the periods’ long‐run marginal costs,
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\mathrm{MC}\,_{2}-\mathrm{MC}\,_{1}$ \end{document}
               , is the supplier’s direct cost of using operations to accommodate cyclical demand. When economical, the use of two plants or one plant and storage narrows this difference but cannot eliminate it unless storage is costless (see Crew and Kleindorfer1979).

The financial market is perfect, with one exception discussed below, and information is symmetric. The supplier is a price‐taker in this financial market and faces the term structure of riskless interest rates described byequation (7). This term structure’s salient feature is the parameter ε that represents the term premium that Fama (1984) found in short‐term interest rates and that Dhillon and Lasser (1998) found throughout the maturity spectrum. Importantly,equation (7)is consistent with yield curves that are upward sloping, downward sloping, or flat, depending on the values ofr
               1, ρ, and ε.

