               .8

fn.p:
Profit as defined in this model is an approximation to the supplier’s market value. This approximation relies on the fact that
                        \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\mathrm{exp}\,( k) \cong 1+k$ \end{document}
                     . The error from using this approximation for market value is small whenkis small. The error from using this approximation to determine the difference in market value from using different financing policies is even smaller.

sec.p:
I derive the sufficient conditions for using some short‐term debt by comparing financing costs while holding the supplier’s operations (output, prices, plant capacity, etc.) constant. The amount of financing required in periodiis fixed in this situation and equal to capacity cost plus periodi’s production costs,
