               in period 2.

The only difference between the financing alternatives when output is held constant is the term premium and flotation costs that the supplier pays. A supplier that uses all long‐term financing (LT) pays the largest term premium because the amount of the loan equals the supplier’s peak financing requirement,
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $q_{2}( B+b) $ \end{document}
               . The supplier pays the smallest flotation cost under this alternative, however, because there is only one loan.

A supplier that uses a mixture of short‐ and long‐term debt (ST&LT) pays a lower term premium than if it used all long‐term debt because a short‐term loan of
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $( q_{2}-q_{1}) b$ \end{document}
               dollars replaces part of the long‐term loan as the source of extra financing needed during the peak period. Adopting this policy does not change the variable portion of the supplier’s flotation costs because there is a one‐for‐one substitution of short‐term debt for long‐term debt. The supplier must pay the fixed component of flotation costs on the additional, short‐term loan, however. Consequently, a mixture of short‐ and long‐term debt is preferable to all long‐term debt when the term premium savings are greater than the incremental fixed flotation cost,
