               . Simplifying this inequality gives the sufficient condition shown in partcof proposition 1.

Partaof proposition 1 gives the sufficient condition for using a mixture of short‐ and long‐term debt that provides maturity matching as observed by Guedes and Opler (1996), Stohs and Mauer (1996), and Demirgüç‐Kunt and Maksimovic (1999). This condition is more likely to be satisfied when the term premium is large, the fixed component of the loan initiation fee is small, production costs are high, and there is a large difference between peak and off‐peak demand. The last effect is particularly important because it establishes that suppliers facing cyclical demand may use a mixture of short‐ and long‐term debt to match the maturity of their assets and liabilities, although suppliers facing uniform demand,
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $q_{2}=q_{1}$ \end{document}
               , will not.

Equations(13a)and(13b), which are derived in the appendix, are the supplier’s long‐run marginal costs of supplying periods 1 and 2 when it uses all long‐term debt. The marginal cost of supplying period 1 equals the supplier’s per unit production cost,b, plus a financing cost that equals the opportunity cost of increasing production rather than holding financial slack. Capacity costs do not affect period 1’s marginal cost because the supplier’s plant is partially idle during this off‐peak period. The marginal cost of supplying period 2 is the incremental cost of increasing plant capacity and output,
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $B+b$ \end{document}
               , plus the net cost of financing these expenditures. This financing cost equals the variable component of the loan initiation fee plus two periods’ interest on the long‐term loan minus the interest income the supplier earns by holding the addition to period 1’s excess funds in financial slack.

